Welcome to The Wardrobe Project Guide: Commit to Clean Out + Sharpen Your Style. 

After being at editor at Bazaar + Vogue for over 20 years, I had amassed a fair amount of clothing. When I downsized, I went through a rather radical closet clean out and sent over 250 (!) items to resale and donated and recycled more. After I successfully completed this, it felt really good. I knew I wanted to create a system based on my experience to help others. 

I’ve been writing for four years about learning to Live with Less and Buy Fewer Better Things, so I’ve culminated my work into this guide which you can download to help you jump start a zero-waste closet clean out and sharpen your editing skills. You can purchase it on my site ($30). The link is also in stories. Also note, I have a new IG account, @thewardrobeprojectnyc where you can follow updates and tips. I hope you find the guide as useful as I and many of my clients have. Also suggestions/questions/thoughts are always encouraged! 
xx Jennifer

Do you have a Signature Style? Are you true to it? From my years of experience, the people I’ve come to meet and know who have the best style (some are quite famous for it) learn to stick with what works and rarely stray from their core favorites. They are known for their signature style; the result of their keen eye and constant editing. This is why I believe a thorough closet clean out, that starts with being thoughtful and making lists, not piles on your bed, will help bring more focus to your style. See my new @thewardrobeprojectnyc guide which I developed to help myself and others. Maybe it’s time for learn to Live with Less and Sharpen Your Style. #thewardrobeproject #closetorganization #closet #closetcleanout #styletips #editor #fewerbetterthings #signaturestyle

It is very hard to know what makes sense when an old friend suddenly passes. Erin and I were friends when our kids, who are close in age, were young (her middle child and my daughter were in class together). She was a kind, deeply involved mother, wickedly funny, and elegant. Her home was a gathering spot, because her hospitality and warmth made everyone want to be a part of her world. We found ourselves in Palm Beach with our parents and in Nantucket in the summer. We drifted apart as our children grew, but would run into each other on occasion and pick up where we had left off. I am not writing this post for condolence comments. I am writing it because I want her to be celebrated (this photo is from Saturday’s SNL, a place she worked for years). I found out about her passing the day after my birthday, while I was on vacation. I was so thankful to celebrate my bday with my husband and children and after hearing the news, beyond the immediate shock, I was profoundly moved to enjoy every moment I have with the people I love. I wish Erin’s family love and peace. May we all focus on the here and now and what matters most.

To celebrate the first year of my jewelry collection, I am thrilled to introduce my large J and petite JJ Cases, memento pendants crafted in 18k solid gold designed to hold personal stories. 

A love letter, a poem, a lyric, a date, a name…Have meaningful moments engraved (in your own handwriting if you desire) on a gold card insert or create your own memento to put inside. 

I love sentimental jewelry, but also am relatively private; I designed these cases as an elegant, discreet way to celebrate and commemorate. 

Hand-crafted by artisans in New York City using century-old techniques and machinery, these designs are inspired by Vesta cases from the 1800s which held matches. All case gold is certified ethically sourced; diamonds are conflict free. 

There are currently two petite JJ case designs (my nickname growing up) and one large J case. The case is going to be my “canvas” so stay tuned for more designs. I hope you love them as much as I do, for anyone who knows me they have been a labor of love!

xx Jennifer

Some of my best fashion memories are interviewing Karl during couture and spending time in the atelier watching his vision come to life, followed by a dinner at his hotel particulier. I was a young journalist and awestruck by the conversation and company (if I remember correctly Linda Evangelists took me on a tour of his home). I also learned Karl had a deep curiosity, could read in several languages and had wide-ranging knowledge of so many topics. He was a cultural sponge, and it opened my eyes to the possibility that fashion could be so much more than frocks. #karllagerfeld

Loved reading @jellison22’s interview with Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen in @fthtsi. I appreciate their deliberate reluctance to share much with their audience though I would happily take more. Years back, I was hired by their ad agency to come up with text for their brand book. I knew it would be hard, close to impossible because they do everything to avoid giving “labels” or thoughts to the clothes they design. Talking about their designs or ethos would never fly, so I chose a passage from Joan Didion’s Play It As It Lays. This was before Didion became a Celine poster model. What words did they ultimately choose? None. @therow last image @grayantiques
